,"1325–1376":"1325–1376","1287–1360":"1287–1360","1287–Female":"1287–Deceased","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1287":"1287","1360":"1360","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Weston, Suffolk, England":"Weston, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kemp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: status name for a champion, Middle English and Middle Low German <i>kempe</i>. In the Middle Ages a champion was a professional fighter on behalf of others; for example the King's Champion, at the coronation, had the duty of issuing a general challenge to battle to anyone who denied the king's right to the throne. The Middle English word corresponds to Old English <i>cempa</i> and Old Norse <i>kempa</i> ‘warrior’; both these go back to ancient Germanic <i>campo</i> ‘warrior’, which is the source of the Dutch and North German name, corresponding to High German   Kampf  .","Dutch and North German (North Rhine-Westphalia): from the personal name <i>Kempe</i>, <i>Kampe</i>; see 1 above.","Dutch and Flemish: metonymic occupational name for someone who grew or processed hemp, from Middle Dutch <i>canep</i> ‘hemp’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kampf","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (mainly <b>Kämpf</b>): from Middle High German <i>kampf</i>, German <i>Kamf</i> ‘fight, struggle’, hence an occupational name for a champion, a professional fighter (see   Kemp  ), or a nickname for someone with a pugnacious temperament. As a Jewish name it can be artificial. Compare   Kaempf  .","German: extended form of   Kamp   1."]},{"name":"Kemps","meanings":["Dutch and Flemish: genitivized form of   Kemp   2 or 4, concentrated in North Brabant and adjacent northern Belgium.","English (London): variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempt","meanings":["Scottish and English: perhaps from a shortened form of the extinct Scottish surname <i>Kemptie</i>, of uncertain origin, or an altered form of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Ilse.  Scandinavian Detlev, Gunhild.","English, Scottish, Dutch, and North German: variant of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempel","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempke","meanings":["North German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempker","meanings":["German: diminutive of   Kemp  ."]},{"name":"Kempkes","meanings":["North German and Dutch: genitivized pet form of   Kemp   2. Particularly in North Rhine-Westphalia and adjacent Gelderland."]},{"name":"Kempner","meanings":["German:","occupational name for a champion at jousting or wrestling, an agent derivative of <i>Kempe</i> ‘fight’ (see   Kemp  ).","habitational name, with agent suffix <i>-er</i>, for someone from any of various places called Kempen (notably near Krefeld) or from Kempno near Poznań, Poland."]}]},{"name":"Allen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alan  , in Britain generally found only as a surname, but in North America equally common as a given name."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Allen Kemp was born in 1300, in Weston, Suffolk, England, his father, William Kempe, was 13 and his mother, Elenor de Barnstaple, was 13. He married Isabelle Hastings. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1347, in his hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1300–1347":"1300–1347","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1287–1360":"1287–1360","1287–Female":"1287–Surnud","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1287":"1287","1360":"1360","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Weston, Suffolk, England":"Weston, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1300–1347":"1300–1347","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1287–1360":"1287–1360","1287–Female":"1287–Kuollut","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1287":"1287","1360":"1360","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Weston, Suffolk, England":"Weston, Suffolk, England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1300–1347":"1300–1347","1302–Male":"1302–Décédé","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1287–1360":"1287–1360","1287–Female":"1287–Décédée","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1287":"1287","1360":"1360","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Weston, Suffolk, England":"Weston, Suffolk, Angleterre","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Allen Kemp est né en 1300, à Weston, Suffolk, Angleterre, son père, William Kempe, avait 13 ans et sa mère, Elenor de Barnstaple, avait 13 ans. Il a épousé Isabelle Hastings. Ils ont eu au moins 1